All specimens were excavated from Pit B, Quadrats 1 and 3, Unit 3, in the main chamber of Leaena’s Breath Cave, between 85 and 120 cm below the sediment floor. Leaena’s Breath Cave has a vertical solution pipe entrance approximately 20 m deep, through which the specimens of
Ce. bairdi
are presumed to have accumulated via pitfall trapping. The roof window of the cave is thought to have been open and accumulating fossils at intervals during the Early to Middle Pleistocene, and was then sealed by a calcrete cap until recently. The holotype was excavated by G. J. P. from Pit B, Quadrat 1, at a depth of 115– 120 cm beneath the sediment floor, on Friday 10 May 2013 . Fine-grained sediments in Unit 3 are of reversed magnetic polarity, which along with the overall species composition of the assemblage, indicate an Early Pleistocene age> 780 kyr BP (Matuyama Reversed Chron;
Prideaux et al. , 2007
). This falls within the Naracoortean land mammal age (
Megirian et al. , 2010
).
